05A05

The Möbius function of permutations with an indecomposable lower bound

Robert Brignall, David Marchant

School of Mathematics and Statistics
The Open University, Milton Keynes, MK7 6AA, UK
Abstract

We show that the Möbius function of an interval in a permutation poset where the lower bound is sum (resp. skew) indecomposable depends solely on the sum (resp. skew) indecomposable permutations contained in the upper bound, and that this can simplify the calculation of the Möbius sum. For increasing oscillations, we give a recursion for the Möbius sum which only involves evaluating simple inequalities.

1 Introduction

Let σ𝜎\sigma and π𝜋\pi be permutations of natural numbers, written in one-line notation, with σ=σ1​σ2​…​σm𝜎subscript𝜎1subscript𝜎2…subscript𝜎𝑚\sigma=\sigma_{1}\sigma_{2}\ldots\sigma_{m}, and π=π1​π2​…​πn𝜋subscript𝜋1subscript𝜋2…subscript𝜋𝑛\pi=\pi_{1}\pi_{2}\ldots\pi_{n}. We say that σ𝜎\sigma is contained in π𝜋\pi if there is a sequence 1≤i1<i2<…<im≤n1subscript𝑖1subscript𝑖2…subscript𝑖𝑚𝑛1\leq i_{1}<i_{2}<\ \ldots<i_{m}\leq n such that for any r,s∈{1,…,m}𝑟𝑠1…𝑚r,s\in\{1,\ldots,m\}, πir<πissubscript𝜋subscript𝑖𝑟subscript𝜋subscript𝑖𝑠\pi_{i_{r}}<\pi_{i_{s}} if and only if σr<σssubscript𝜎𝑟subscript𝜎𝑠\sigma_{r}<\sigma_{s}. We say that π𝜋\pi avoids σ𝜎\sigma if π𝜋\pi does not contain σ𝜎\sigma. The set of all permutations is a poset under the partial order given by containment.

A closed interval [σ,π]𝜎𝜋[\sigma,\pi] in a poset is the set defined as {τ:σ≤τ≤π}conditional-set𝜏𝜎𝜏𝜋\{\tau:\sigma\leq\tau\leq\pi\}. A half-open interval [σ,π)𝜎𝜋[\sigma,\pi) is the set {τ:σ≤τ<π}conditional-set𝜏𝜎𝜏𝜋\{\tau:\sigma\leq\tau<\pi\}. The Möbius function μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi] is defined on an interval of a poset as follows: for σ≰πnot-less-than-nor-greater-than𝜎𝜋\sigma\nleq\pi, μ​[σ,π]=0𝜇𝜎𝜋0\mu[\sigma,\pi]=0; for all λ𝜆\lambda, μ​[λ,λ]=1𝜇𝜆𝜆1\mu[\lambda,\lambda]=1; and for σ<π𝜎𝜋\sigma<\pi,

μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\displaystyle\mu[\sigma,\pi] =−∑λ∈[σ,π)μ​[σ,λ].absentsubscript𝜆𝜎𝜋𝜇𝜎𝜆\displaystyle=-\sum_{\lambda\in[\sigma,\pi)}\mu[\sigma,\lambda]. (1)

Our motivation for this paper is to find a contributing set ℭσ,πsubscriptℭ𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi} that is significantly smaller than the poset interval [σ,π)𝜎𝜋[\sigma,\pi), and a {0,±1}0plus-or-minus1\{0,\pm 1\} weighting function W​(σ,α,π)𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi) such that

μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\displaystyle\mu[\sigma,\pi] =−∑α∈ℭσ,πμ​[σ,α]​W​(σ,α,π).absentsubscript𝛼subscriptℭ𝜎𝜋𝜇𝜎𝛼𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋\displaystyle=-\sum_{\alpha\in\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi}}\mu[\sigma,\alpha]W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi). (2)

Plainly, in Equation 2, we could set ℭσ,π=[σ,π)subscriptℭ𝜎𝜋𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi}=[\sigma,\pi), and W​(σ,α,π)=1𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋1W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi)=1, which is equivalent to Equation 1.

One approach here would be to take a permutation β𝛽\beta such that σ<β<π𝜎𝛽𝜋\sigma<\beta<\pi. We could then set ℭσ,π={λ:λ∈[σ,π)​ and ​λ∉[σ,β]}subscriptℭ𝜎𝜋conditional-set𝜆𝜆𝜎𝜋 and 𝜆𝜎𝛽\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi}=\{\lambda:\lambda\in[\sigma,\pi)\text{ and }\lambda\not\in[\sigma,\beta]\}, and W​(σ,α,π)=1𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋1W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi)=1, since, from Equation 2, ∑λ∈[σ,β]μ​[σ,λ]=0subscript𝜆𝜎𝛽𝜇𝜎𝜆0\sum_{\lambda\in[\sigma,\beta]}\mu[\sigma,\lambda]=0. This approach was used in Smith [5], who determined the Möbius function on the interval [1,π]1𝜋[1,\pi] for all permutations π𝜋\pi with a single descent. Smith’s paper is unusual, in that it provides an explicit formula for the value of the Möbius function.

Our approach is different. We identify individual elements (say λ𝜆\lambda), of the poset that have μ​[σ,λ]=0𝜇𝜎𝜆0\mu[\sigma,\lambda]=0. We also show that there are pairs of elements, λ𝜆\lambda and λ′superscript𝜆′\lambda^{\prime}, where μ​[σ,λ]=−μ​[σ,λ′]𝜇𝜎𝜆𝜇𝜎superscript𝜆′\mu[\sigma,\lambda]=-\mu[\sigma,\lambda^{\prime}], and so we can exclude these pairs of elements. Finally, we show that there are quartets of permutations λ1,…,λ4subscript𝜆1…subscript𝜆4\lambda_{1},\ldots,\lambda_{4} where ∑i=14μ​[σ,λi]=0superscriptsubscript𝑖14𝜇𝜎subscript𝜆𝑖0\sum_{i=1}^{4}\mu[\sigma,\lambda_{i}]=0; and that we can systematically identify these quartets. By excluding these permutations from ℭσ,πsubscriptℭ𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi} we can significantly reduce the number of elements in ℭσ,πsubscriptℭ𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi} compared to the number of elements in the interval [σ,π)𝜎𝜋[\sigma,\pi). This approach results in the ability to compute μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi], where σ𝜎\sigma is indecomposable, much faster than evaluating Equation 1. For increasing oscillations, we will show that the elements of ℭσ,πsubscriptℭ𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi} can be determined using simple inequalities, and that as a consequence μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi] can be determined using inequalities. With this approach, we have computed μ​[1,π]𝜇1𝜋\mu[1,\pi], where π𝜋\pi is an increasing oscillation, up to |π|=2,000,000𝜋2,000,000\left\lvert\pi\right\rvert=\text{2,000,000}.

The study of the Möbius function in the permutation poset was introduced by Wilf [9]. The first result in this area was by Sagan and Vatter [4], who determined the Möbius function on intervals of layered permutations. Steingrímsson and Tenner [8] found a large class of pairs of permutations (σ,π)𝜎𝜋(\sigma,\pi) where μ​[σ,π]=0𝜇𝜎𝜋0\mu[\sigma,\pi]=0, as well as determining the Möbius function where σ𝜎\sigma occurs exactly once in π𝜋\pi, and σ𝜎\sigma and π𝜋\pi satisfy certain other conditions. Burstein, Jelínek, Jelínková and Steingrímsson [1] found a recursion for the Möbius function for sum/skew decomposable permutations in terms of the sum/skew indecomposable permutations in the lower and upper bounds. They also found a method to determine the Möbius function for separable permutations by counting embeddings. We use the recursions for decomposable permutations to underpin the first part of this paper. McNamara and Steingrímsson [3] investigated the topology of intervals in the permutation poset, and found a single recurrence equivalent to the recursions in [1].

Many results for μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi] have been obtained by considering ways in which σ𝜎\sigma can be found in π𝜋\pi, which we call an embedding of σ𝜎\sigma in π𝜋\pi, although typically only some of the embeddings (“normal embeddings”) are counted. In [6], Smith used normal embeddings to determine the Möbius function μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi] when σ𝜎\sigma and π𝜋\pi have the same number of descents.

One problem with embeddings arises in cases such as μ​[1,24153]𝜇124153\mu[1,24153]. Here there are plainly only five ways to embed the permutation 111 into 241532415324153, however μ​[1,24153]=6𝜇1241536\mu[1,24153]=6, and thus the embedding approach is not sufficient.

One possible solution to this issue is to count the normal embeddings and then add a “correction factor”. This approach was used by Smith in [7]. The result applies to all intervals in the permutation poset, although the correction factor is a rather complicated double sum, which still involves ∑λ∈[σ,π)μ​[σ,λ]subscript𝜆𝜎𝜋𝜇𝜎𝜆\sum_{\lambda\in[\sigma,\pi)}\mu[\sigma,\lambda].

In this paper we show that the Möbius function on intervals with a sum indecomposable lower bound depends only on the sum indecomposable permutations contained in the upper bound. We provide a weighting function that determines which sum indecomposable permutations contribute to the Möbius sum. We then consider increasing oscillations. For these permutations, we show how we can find all of the permutations that contribute to the Möbius sum by applying simple numeric inequalities, which leads to a fast polynomial algorithm for determining the Möbius function.

We start with some essential definitions and notation in Section 2, then in Section 3 we provide a number of preliminary lemmas. We conclude this section with a theorem that gives μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi], where σ𝜎\sigma is a sum indecomposable permutation, for all π𝜋\pi. In Section 4 we consider μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi] where σ𝜎\sigma is a sum indecomposable permutation, and π𝜋\pi is an increasing oscillation. We finish with some concluding remarks in Section 5.

2 Definitions and notation

When discussing the Möbius function, μ​[σ,π]=−∑λ∈[σ,π)μ​[σ,λ]𝜇𝜎𝜋subscript𝜆𝜎𝜋𝜇𝜎𝜆\mu[\sigma,\pi]=-\sum_{\lambda\in[\sigma,\pi)}\mu[\sigma,\lambda], we will frequently be examining the value of μ​[σ,λ]𝜇𝜎𝜆\mu[\sigma,\lambda] for a specific permutation λ𝜆\lambda. We say that this is the contribution that λ𝜆\lambda makes to the sum. If we have a set of permutations S⊆[σ,π)𝑆𝜎𝜋S\subseteq[\sigma,\pi) such that ∑λ∈Sμ​[σ,λ]=0subscript𝜆𝑆𝜇𝜎𝜆0\sum_{\lambda\in S}\mu[\sigma,\lambda]=0, then we say that the set S𝑆S makes no net contribution to the sum.

A sum of two permutations α𝛼\alpha and β𝛽\beta of lengths m𝑚m and n𝑛n respectively is the permutation α1,…,αm,β1+m,…,βn+msubscript𝛼1…subscript𝛼𝑚subscript𝛽1𝑚…subscript𝛽𝑛𝑚\alpha_{1},\ldots,\alpha_{m},\beta_{1}+m,\ldots,\beta_{n}+m. We write a sum as α⊕βdirect-sum𝛼𝛽\alpha\oplus\beta. A skew sum, α⊖βsymmetric-difference𝛼𝛽\alpha\ominus\beta, is the permutation α1+n,…,αm+n,β1,…,βnsubscript𝛼1𝑛…subscript𝛼𝑚𝑛subscript𝛽1…subscript𝛽𝑛\alpha_{1}+n,\ldots,\alpha_{m}+n,\beta_{1},\ldots,\beta_{n}. As examples, 321⊕213=321546direct-sum321213321546321\oplus 213=321546, and 321⊖213=654213symmetric-difference321213654213321\ominus 213=654213, and these are shown in Figure 1. A sum-indecomposable (resp. skew-indecomposable) permutation is a permutation that cannot be written as the sum (resp. skew-sum) of two smaller permutations.

Let α𝛼\alpha be a permutation, and r𝑟r a positive integer. Then ⊕rαsuperscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼\oplus^{r}\alpha is α⊕α⊕…⊕α⊕αdirect-sum𝛼𝛼…𝛼𝛼\alpha\oplus\alpha\oplus\ldots\oplus\alpha\oplus\alpha, with r𝑟r occurrences of α𝛼\alpha. If S𝑆S is a set of permutations, then ⊕rS=∪λ∈S{⊕rλ}superscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝑆subscript𝜆𝑆superscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝜆\oplus^{r}S=\cup_{\lambda\in S}\{\oplus^{r}\lambda\}.

The interleave of two permutations α𝛼\alpha and β𝛽\beta is formed by taking the sum α⊕βdirect-sum𝛼𝛽\alpha\oplus\beta, and then exchanging the value of the largest point from α𝛼\alpha with the value of the smallest point from β𝛽\beta. We can also view this as increasing the largest point from α𝛼\alpha by 1, and simultaneously decreasing the smallest point from β𝛽\beta by 1. We write an interleave as α⦸β⦸𝛼𝛽\alpha\obslash\beta. For example, 321⦸213=421536⦸321213421536321\obslash 213=421536, see Figure 1.

For completeness, we also define a skew interleave, α⊘β⊘𝛼𝛽\alpha\oslash\beta, which is formed by taking the skew sum α⊖βsymmetric-difference𝛼𝛽\alpha\ominus\beta, and then exchanging the smallest point from α𝛼\alpha with the largest point from β𝛽\beta. As an example, 321⊘213=653214⊘321213653214321\oslash 213=653214, as shown in Figure 1.

The interleave operations, ⦸⦸\obslash and ⊘⊘\oslash, are not associative, as 1⦸1⦸1⦸11⦸11\obslash 1\obslash 1 could represent 231231231 or 312312312. To avoid this ambiguity, we require that the permutation 111 can either be interleaved to the left or to the right, but not both. It is easy to see that this restriction establishes associativity. We note here that, with this restriction, an expression involving ⊕direct-sum\oplus and ⦸⦸\obslash represents a unique permutation regardless of the order in which the operations are applied.

Let α𝛼\alpha be a permutation with length greater than 1. We will frequently want to refer to permutations that have the form α⦸α⦸…⦸α⦸α⦸𝛼𝛼⦸…⦸𝛼⦸𝛼\alpha\obslash\alpha\obslash\ldots\obslash\alpha\obslash\alpha. For the remainder of this paper, by symmetry it suffices to discuss permutations in relation to sums and interleaves only. For the same reason, references to (in)decomposable permutations may omit the “sum” qualifier.

An interval of a permutation is a set of contiguous positions where the set of values is also contiguous. A simple permutation is one where the permutation contains no intervals other than those of length one, and the entire permutation.

3 Preliminary lemmas and main theorem

In this section our aim is to show that if σ𝜎\sigma is indecomposable, then for any π≥σ𝜋𝜎\pi\geq\sigma there is a {0,±1}0plus-or-minus1\{0,\pm 1\} weighting function W​(σ,α,π)𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi) and a set of permutations ℭσ,πsubscriptℭ𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi}, such that

μ​[σ,π]=−∑α∈ℭσ,πμ​[σ,α]​W​(σ,α,π).𝜇𝜎𝜋subscript𝛼subscriptℭ𝜎𝜋𝜇𝜎𝛼𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi]=-\sum_{\alpha\in\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi}}\mu[\sigma,\alpha]W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi).

If π𝜋\pi is the identity permutation 12​…​n12…𝑛12\ldots n or its reverse, then μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi] is trivial for any σ𝜎\sigma, and we exclude the identity and its reverse from being the upper bound of any interval under consideration.

As noted earlier, our approach is to show that there are permutations, pairs of permutations, and quartets of permutations in [σ,π)𝜎𝜋[\sigma,\pi) that make no net contribution to the sum.

4 Increasing oscillations

We now move on to increasing oscillations. Given an indecomposable permutation σ𝜎\sigma, and an increasing oscillation π𝜋\pi, our aim in this section is to describe ℭσ,πsubscriptℭ𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi} in precise terms. We will find a sum for the Möbius function, μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi], which only requires the evaluation of simple inequalities.

If π𝜋\pi is an increasing oscillation with length less than 4, then μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\mu[\sigma,\pi] is trivial to determine for any σ𝜎\sigma. For the remainder of this section we assume that π𝜋\pi has length at least 4.

We partition the set of increasing oscillations with length greater than 1 into five disjoint subsets. These subsets are {21},21\{21\},\; {⦸k+121},superscript⦸𝑘1absent21\{\obslash^{{k+1}}21\},\; {1⦸(⦸k21)},\{1\obslash\left(\obslash^{k}21\right)\},\; {(⦸k21)⦸1},\{\left(\obslash^{k}21\right)\obslash 1\},\; and {1⦸(⦸k21)⦸1}\{1\obslash\left(\obslash^{k}21\right)\obslash 1\}, where k𝑘k is a positive integer. If two increasing oscillations are in the same subset, then we say that they have the same shape.

We now determine what permutations contained in an increasing oscillation have a non-zero contribution to the Möbius sum.

Furthermore, we will see that this weight function is only used when σ≤⊕rα≤π𝜎superscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼𝜋\sigma\leq\oplus^{r}\alpha\leq\pi.

We are now in a position to state our main theorem for this section. In this theorem, we consider the contribution to the Möbius sum of each possible shape of some sum indecomposable α𝛼\alpha. There are five possible shapes, and, given that the expression for each shape is identical, we abuse notation slightly by writing our theorem as a sum over the shapes, thus the first sum in Theorem 19 is over the possible shapes of α𝛼\alpha, where four of the shapes have a parameter k𝑘k. For each shape, the limits on the interior sum determine the minimum and maximum values of k𝑘k, using the summation variable v𝑣v. We use the notation αvsubscript𝛼𝑣\alpha_{v} to represent the actual permutation that has the shape α𝛼\alpha, where the parameter k𝑘k has been set to the value of v𝑣v. As an example, if α=1⦸(⦸k21)\alpha=1\obslash\left(\obslash^{k}21\right), and v=2𝑣2v=2, then αv=1⦸(⦸221)=24153\alpha_{v}=1\obslash\left(\obslash^{2}21\right)=24153.

Theorem 19.

Let π𝜋\pi be an increasing oscillation, and let σ≤π𝜎𝜋\sigma\leq\pi be sum indecomposable. Then

μ​[σ,π]𝜇𝜎𝜋\displaystyle\mu[\sigma,\pi] =∑α∈𝒮∑v=MinK⁡(σ,α)MaxK⁡(α,π)μ​[σ,αv]​Wi​o​(σ,αv,π)absentsubscript𝛼𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑣MinK𝜎𝛼MaxK𝛼𝜋𝜇𝜎subscript𝛼𝑣subscript𝑊𝑖𝑜𝜎subscript𝛼𝑣𝜋\displaystyle=\sum_{\alpha\in\mathcal{S}}\ \sum_{v=\operatorname{MinK}(\sigma,\alpha)}^{\operatorname{MaxK}(\alpha,\pi)}\mu[\sigma,\alpha_{v}]W_{io}(\sigma,\alpha_{v},\pi)

where the first sum is over the possible shapes of a sum indecomposable permutation contained in an increasing oscillation, so 𝒮={21,\mathcal{S}=\{21,\; ⦸k+121,superscript⦸𝑘1absent21\obslash^{{k+1}}21,\; 1⦸(⦸k21),1\obslash\left(\obslash^{k}21\right),\; (⦸k21)⦸1,\left(\obslash^{k}21\right)\obslash 1,\; 1⦸(⦸k21)⦸1}1\obslash\left(\obslash^{k}21\right)\obslash 1\}.

Proof.

By Lemma 11 the only sum-decomposable permutations contained in an increasing oscillation that contribute to the Möbius sum are ℱ⊕​(⊕rα)subscriptℱdirect-sumsuperscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼\mathcal{F}_{\oplus}(\oplus^{r}\alpha), where α∈𝒮𝛼𝒮\alpha\in\mathcal{S}.

If we set r=1𝑟1r=1, then for each α𝛼\alpha in 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S} Lemma 18 provides the smallest value of k𝑘k such that σ≤α𝜎𝛼\sigma\leq\alpha. If there is no such value of k𝑘k, then we use |π|𝜋\left\lvert\pi\right\rvert, as the maximum value of k𝑘k must be smaller than this, and so the sum is empty.

Again setting r=1𝑟1r=1, for each α𝛼\alpha in 𝒮𝒮\mathcal{S} Lemma 16 provides the maximum value of k𝑘k such that α≤π𝛼𝜋\alpha\leq\pi. If there is no value of k𝑘k that satisfies the inequality, then we set MaxK⁡(α,π)=0MaxK𝛼𝜋0\operatorname{MaxK}(\alpha,\pi)=0, thus forcing the sum to be empty.

Thus the permutations αvsubscript𝛼𝑣\alpha_{v} in the sum

∑α∈𝒮∑v=MinK⁡(σ,α)MaxK⁡(α,π)subscript𝛼𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑣MinK𝜎𝛼MaxK𝛼𝜋\sum_{\alpha\in\mathcal{S}}\ \sum_{v=\operatorname{MinK}(\sigma,\alpha)}^{\operatorname{MaxK}(\alpha,\pi)}

are those that could contribute to the Möbius sum, and for any αvsubscript𝛼𝑣\alpha_{v} not included in the sum, ℱ⊕​(⊕rαv)subscriptℱdirect-sumsuperscriptdirect-sum𝑟subscript𝛼𝑣\mathcal{F}_{\oplus}(\oplus^{r}\alpha_{v}) has a zero contribution to the Möbius sum for any r𝑟r.

Further, we can see from the construction method that any αvsubscript𝛼𝑣\alpha_{v} included in the sum has σ≤⊕rαv≤π𝜎superscriptdirect-sum𝑟subscript𝛼𝑣𝜋\sigma\leq\oplus^{r}\alpha_{v}\leq\pi for at least one value of r𝑟r, as if this was not the case, then we would have MinK⁡(σ,α)>MaxK⁡(α,π)MinK𝜎𝛼MaxK𝛼𝜋\operatorname{MinK}(\sigma,\alpha)>\operatorname{MaxK}(\alpha,\pi), and so the sum would be empty.

We have therefore shown that the αvsubscript𝛼𝑣\alpha_{v}-s included in the sum form a contributing set, and we could therefore set ℭσ,πsubscriptℭ𝜎𝜋\mathfrak{C}_{\sigma,\pi} to be those αvsubscript𝛼𝑣\alpha_{v}-s, and use Theorem 10. We now show that the increasing oscillation weight function Wi​o​(σ,α,π)subscript𝑊𝑖𝑜𝜎𝛼𝜋W_{io}(\sigma,\alpha,\pi) is equivalent to W​(σ,α,π)𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi) as defined in the general case.

By Corollary 17, if (⊕rα)⊕1≰πnot-less-than-or-equalsdirect-sumsuperscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼1𝜋\left(\oplus^{r}\alpha\right)\oplus 1\not\leq\pi then 1⊕(⊕rα)≰πnot-less-than-or-equalsdirect-sum1superscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼𝜋1\oplus\left(\oplus^{r}\alpha\right)\not\leq\pi and vice-versa, and so the condition for (⊕rα)⊕1direct-sumsuperscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼1\left(\oplus^{r}\alpha\right)\oplus 1 also covers 1⊕(⊕rα)direct-sum1superscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼1\oplus\left(\oplus^{r}\alpha\right). As discussed above, we know that there is at least one value of r𝑟r such that σ≤⊕rα≤π𝜎superscriptdirect-sum𝑟𝛼𝜋\sigma\leq\oplus^{r}\alpha\leq\pi, and so Wi​o​(σ,α,π)subscript𝑊𝑖𝑜𝜎𝛼𝜋W_{io}(\sigma,\alpha,\pi) does not need to include this condition. Thus the increasing oscillation weight function Wi​o​(σ,α,π)subscript𝑊𝑖𝑜𝜎𝛼𝜋W_{io}(\sigma,\alpha,\pi) is equivalent to W​(σ,α,π)𝑊𝜎𝛼𝜋W(\sigma,\alpha,\pi) as defined in the general case. ∎

5 Concluding remarks

The results in [1] provide two recurrences to handle the case where π𝜋\pi is decomposable. This work handles the case where σ𝜎\sigma is indecomposable. It overlaps with [1] when σ𝜎\sigma is indecomposable and π𝜋\pi is decomposable. This leaves the case where σ𝜎\sigma is decomposable and π𝜋\pi is indecomposable for further investigation.

We can see that by symmetry μ​[σ,Wn]=μ​[σ−1,Mn]𝜇𝜎subscript𝑊𝑛𝜇superscript𝜎1subscript𝑀𝑛\mu[\sigma,W_{n}]=\mu[\sigma^{-1},M_{n}]. If we consider the value of the principal Möbius function, μ​[1,π]𝜇1𝜋\mu[1,\pi], where π𝜋\pi is either Wnsubscript𝑊𝑛W_{n} or Mnsubscript𝑀𝑛M_{n}, then it is simple to show that the absolute value of the principal Möbius function is bounded above by 2nsuperscript2𝑛2^{n}. The weight function for increasing oscillations can be ±1plus-or-minus1\pm 1, and we can see no obvious reason why there should not be two distinct values, i𝑖i and j𝑗j, with the same parity, such that the signs of μ​[1,Wi]𝜇1subscript𝑊𝑖\mu[1,W_{i}] and μ​[1,Wj]𝜇1subscript𝑊𝑗\mu[1,W_{j}] were different. We have experimental evidence, based on the values of Wnsubscript𝑊𝑛W_{n} and Mnsubscript𝑀𝑛M_{n} for n=1​…​2,000,000𝑛1…2,000,000n=1\ldots\text{2,000,000} that suggests that μ​[1,W2​n]<0𝜇1subscript𝑊2𝑛0\mu[1,W_{2n}]<0, and that μ​[1,W2​n−1]>0𝜇1subscript𝑊2𝑛10\mu[1,W_{2n-1}]>0.

Figure 6 is a log-log plot of the absolute values of μ​[1,W2​n]𝜇1subscript𝑊2𝑛\mu[1,W_{2n}] from n=8,000𝑛8,000n=\text{8,000} to n=10,000𝑛10,000n=\text{10,000}. As can be seen, there seems to be some evidence of “banding”, and we have confirmed that this pattern continues for all values examined. Examination of the values of μ[1,W2​n−1\mu[1,W_{2n-1}] reveals the same patterns.

The complete nearly-layered permutations are formed by interleaving descending permutations. Formally, a complete nearly-layered permutation has the form

α1⦸α2⦸…⦸αk−1⦸αk⦸subscript𝛼1subscript𝛼2⦸…⦸subscript𝛼𝑘1⦸subscript𝛼𝑘\alpha_{1}\obslash\alpha_{2}\obslash\ldots\obslash\alpha_{k-1}\obslash\alpha_{k}

where each αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i} is a descending permutation, with αi>1subscript𝛼𝑖1\alpha_{i}>1 for i=2,…,k−1𝑖2…𝑘1i=2,\ldots,k-1. If we set αi=21subscript𝛼𝑖21\alpha_{i}=21 for i=2,…,k−1𝑖2…𝑘1i=2,\ldots,k-1, and α1,αk∈{1,21}subscript𝛼1subscript𝛼𝑘121\alpha_{1},\alpha_{k}\in\{1,21\}, then we obtain the increasing oscillations.

The computational approach taken for increasing oscillations could, we think, be adapted to complete nearly-layered permutations. It is clear that the equivalent of the inequalities in Lemmas 16 and 18 would be somewhat more complex than those found here, but we believe that it should be possible to define an algorithm that could determine the Möbius function for complete nearly-layered permutations where the lower bound is sum indecomposable.
